The retail is more than whats meet the eye, there is the consumer that's forever morphing, a technology that ticks behind 24/7, and there is future.
India is a diverse land and home to various situations and lifestyles. One that retail outlets been focussing are the nuclear families.
The nuclear families form a potential consumer base for all the retail in India. Curating retail experience for this sector can be tough because of the
diverse needs and ever floating values, traditions and lifestyle choices of the people comprising this section.
There are tremendous technological reformations in enhancing the retail experience and making the process seamless for the consumer market. Not
only the convenience, but emotional and psychological needs are targeted to bring the best retail experience to the customer in stores.
Mostly the Marketing and technology evangelists
focus on retail experience inside the store, but the whole experience starts way before.
There are a whole lot of thoughts and emotions which goes through a consumer's mind before even they enter the store and use its products or
services. Many of which determines which store they visit.
Retails today use many services that cater to this thought but with growing competition, it has become extremely vital for Retailers to innovate
continuously and engage the consumer in early decision making.

I started with diving straight to the customer experience and getting a basic understanding of their shopping needs, habits and issues. Mainly
because today's customers are not only Go-to-Store customers, they are empowered and efficient people who shop online, offline, on the road, in
house, actually almost everywhere. They are Dynamic shoppers. Reaching to them is smooth and sophisticated at the same time because it's now
not only about achieving them, it's about engaging them.
This project is an attempt to recognise consumer behaviour around today's retail experiences and focusing on what makes the customer actually get
out and visit the store. Also, based on the research will try to align some paradigms and speculate a few scenarios that might prevail in the coming
future for Retail brick and mortar stores.
For my research, I chose a nuclear family of five, age varying from 22 -62 years.

What research methodologies did I use?
Allow quantitative research at a scale which helps understanding trends. They can also be used to narrow down the spectrum of inquiry to areas most relevant to the subject being
Provide an open-ended approach for discussing the subject with people and the data generated is qualitative in nature creating the room for personal & archetype identification.
Observing the user in the environment is really important because during interviews usually 'what they say' is not exactly 'what they do.'
I looked at the initial data collected from the user, followed user trend reports and studied the different aspects of retail shops, which will make them survive the Digital Age.
